defaultOutside the Exploration and Production sector, other areas of Shell business such as downstream fuels and lubricants, corporate activities, and research and development contribute strongly to 
defaultthe UK supply chain. 
defaultShell’s expenditure brings significant income for UK industry and government, as well as delivering a range of additional benefits such as infrastructure, employment, and supporting services.  The long history and high level of activit
defaulty in the UK oil and gas industry has allowed for the development of skills and technological excellence which is exported
default around the globe. 
defaultExamples include contract values to UK companies of around $500 million contributing to Shell projects in Nigeria an
defaultd Iraq and opening up strategic growth markets to UK industry. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe decommissioning of the Brent field in the North Sea opens up significant employment and business opportunities to the local market in the next decades. This includes both skilled and unsk
defaultilled work in services such as transport, scrap handling and waste disposal. In addition, this presents an opportunity to achieve global excellence in decommissioning that can be exported across the globe.  
default&#xa0;
defaultA consortium of Shell, Vopak and Greenergy
default acquired the terminal assets at the Coryton refinery (formerly owned by Petroplus) in September 2012. Redevelopment of the site into an import and distribution terminal called Thames Oilport is underway and the first phase is due
default to be operational in Q4 2
default013. 
defaultThe site has a unique quality as a UK terminal - deep water access, meaning larger ships can bring in finished products directly into the UK market. This will connect the UK market to, for example, the global diesel supply chain, affording long-term a
defaultccess to competitively priced product for UK consumers.
default&#xa0;
defaultShell also contributes to the UK through its social investment programs which focus on enterprise development. Shell Springboard and Shell LiveWIRE provide support to low carbon entrepreneurs and you
defaultng entrepreneurs to start-up and grow their businesses. Support is provided through monthly start up grants, an annual awards programme, networking opportunities and online business advice. LiveWIRE winners contribute approximately 100 jobs to the UK econo
defaultmy each year and £800,000. Winners of both of these programs have gone on to set up successful enterprises such as GlassesDirect.com who won the Shell LiveWIRE Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award in 2005. GlassesDirect.com has grown into a £12 million per
default annum (turnover) online eyewear retailer employing 
defaultmore than 50 staff in the UK. 
defaultThrough these programs to date more than £7.5m has been awarded to entrepreneurs in the UK. 
