defaultIs there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector? Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive defaultindustries and NGOs?default&#xa0;defaultIndustry can achieve more when working in partnership with governments, communities and NGOs. We work closely with NGOs across all areas of our business and believe such collaboration helps us operate more safely and responsibly. Clos
defaulte scrutiny of our industry from the NGO sector helps raise broader public awareness of the energy and environmental dilemmas the world faces. It can help shape government policies for the better, and it can help raise operational standards across the board
default.
defaultAs above, working with experts from leading environmental organisations helps us better understand and address the challenges we face in running our facilities and developing major projects.
default 
defaultThrough our partnerships with leading environmental organisatio
defaultns we continue to find new ways to manage environmental challenges and improve the way we develop our projects. In 2012, Shell worked with 
defaultWetlands International
default on ecosystem baseline studies of the Timan-Pechora region of northern Russia, where Shell is planning a new exploration project.
default 
defaultShell was one of several companies and organisations that commissioned a
defaultn independent study through 
defaultIUCN
default on the relationship between extractive industries and natural World Herita
defaultge sites. The study report proposes practical ways of strengthening the role of the World Heritage Convention in safeguarding these special areas.
default 
defaultOur partnership with 
defaultEarthwatch
default enables Shell employees to work with scientists on research projects around the world. This includes our support for its research and learning programme in the rainforests of the Sabah
default region of Borneo, Malaysia. Our employees are working with scientists to understand the effects of logging and changes in land use, and the resilience of these rainforests to the potential effects of climate change.
default 
defaultWith 
defaultThe Nature Conservancy
default we are working to find ways to use artificially engineered oyster reefs as breakwaters to reduce coastal erosion in Lo
defaultuisiana, USA. This approach can also protect pipelines in the area.
defaultWould increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition from elsewhere or can it be used to make the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corpordefaultate governance?defaultStability in a regulatory regime and a level playing field globally are critical for incentivising the necessary investments in our energy infrastructure; upstream and downstream and maintaining competiveness for UK companies. We welcome ef
defaultfective legislation where it can demonstrate excellence for best practice and corporate governance and can be exported to other countries, thus enhancing the UK’s competitiveness. 
defaultShell is a founder member and strong supporter of the “Extractive Industries
default Transparency Initiative
default”
default (EITI) and therefore welcomes efforts to improve transparency. However,
default it is important to ensure a level playing field globally; so that the UK companies are not competitively disadvantaged. 
defaultWhat is the competitive landscape fordefault the extractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?defaultThere is clear evidence that demonstrates the ongoing role for oil and gas production into the 21
defaultst
default Century. Analysis by the International Energy Agency (IEA, World Energy Outlook, 2012) showed how fossil fuels remain dominant in the global energy mix up to 2035, despite the growth in low carbon sources of energy, in part due to an overall rise in energ
defaulty demand. Clearly, the UK must remain competitive and can do so by offering a stable and streamlined regulatory regime and providing additional policy support where necessary. For example, support for Carbon Capture and Storage is essential to enable it to
default progress through the demonstration phase into commercial deployment. Without such support, CCS will not reach its full potential of helping decarbonise the energy mix and ensuring that energy sources like gas, continue to provide
default&#xa0;
defaultsecure and reliable energ
defaulty supplies. Without these, the benefits that extractive industries can bring to the UK could be limited.
